\f0\b\fs52 \cf0 Tomatillo Salsa\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl240\ql\qnatural

\f1\fs32 \cf2 Serves:  
\b0 \cf0 four 8-ounce jars\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\ql\qnatural

\fs36 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\ql\qnatural

\f0\b\fs44 \cf0 Ingredients\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sl400\ql\qnatural
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs42 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}1 large poblano pepper, stemmed, halved and seeded\
{\listtext	\'95	}1/2 large white onion, cut into 4 wedges\
{\listtext	\'95	}4 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/garlic/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 cloves garlic}}\
{\listtext	\'95	}2 1/4 pounds tomatillos, husked\
{\listtext	\'95	}1/2 teaspoon ground cumin\
{\listtext	\'95	}1/4 cup fresh lime juice or bottled {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/key-lime/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Key lime}} juice\
{\listtext	\'95	}1 tablespoon distilled {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/vinegar/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 white vinegar}}\
{\listtext	\'95	}1 1/2 teaspoons sugar\
{\listtext	\'95	}Kosher salt\
{\listtext	\'95	}3 red {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/jalapeno-chile/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 jalapeno}} peppers, thinly sliced crosswise (with seeds)\
{\listtext	\'95	}Chopped fresh cilantro, for topping (optional)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\ql\qnatural

\f0\b\fs44 \cf0 Directions\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\sa140\ql\qnatural

\f1\b0\fs42 \cf0 Start with our {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodnetwork.com/recipes-and-cooking/how-to-preserve/pictures/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 step-by-step canning how-to}}.\
Sterilize four 8-ounce canning jars and lids.\
Preheat the broiler. Put the poblano halves skin-side up on a foil-lined broiler pan with the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/onion/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 onion}} and garlic. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/broil/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Broil}} until the poblano is charred and the onion and garlic are browned, about 8 minutes. Cool the poblano slightly, then peel.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\sa140\ql\qnatural
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/pulse/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Pulse}} the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/tomatillo/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 tomatillos}} in a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/food-processor/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 food processor}} in batches until coarsely chopped, then transfer to a bowl. Add the poblano, onion and garlic to the processor and pulse until coarsely chopped (do not overprocess). Transfer to a large, wide {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/saucepan/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 saucepan}}. Add the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/cumin/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 cumin}}, lime juice, vinegar, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/sugar/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 sugar}} and 1 tablespoon salt. Bring to a boil over high heat and cook, stirring occasionally, until slightly reduced, 3 to 4 minutes.\
Add the tomatillos and jalapenos to the pan, cover and return to a boil. Cook until heated through, 3 to 4 more minutes.\
Fill the jars with the tomatillo mixture, leaving 3/4 inch headspace, then seal and process. After opening, top the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/salsa/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 salsa}} with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/cilantro/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 cilantro}}, if desired.\
